Z Score normalization

Normalization is essential for this dataset since all the numerical column belongs to different ranges

z_score_normalization <- function(x) {
  return((x - mean(x)) / sd(x))
}
numeric_vars <- c("CementComponent", "WaterComponent", "CoarseAggregateComponent","FineAggregateComponent","AgeInDays","Strength")
data[numeric_vars] <- lapply(data[numeric_vars], z_score_normalization)

Train Test Split

set.seed(123)
test_size <- 0.2
num_test_samples <- round(nrow(data) * test_size)
test_indices <- sample(1:nrow(data), num_test_samples)
train_data <- data[-test_indices, ]  # Training set
test_data <- data[test_indices, ]    # Testing set
cat("Training set dimensions:", dim(train_data), "\n")
## Training set dimensions: 824 6
cat("Testing set dimensions:", dim(test_data), "\n")
## Testing set dimensions: 206 6

Building model

model <- lm(Strength ~  CementComponent + WaterComponent + CoarseAggregateComponent + FineAggregateComponent + AgeInDays, data = train_data)
summary(model)

Evaluation Metrics

predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data)

mean_absolute_error <- mean(abs(predictions - data$Strength))
mean_squared_error <- mean((predictions - data$Strength)^2)
root_mean_squared_error <- sqrt(mean_squared_error)
r_squared <- summary(model)$r.squared
adjusted_r_squared <- summary(model)$adj.r.squared
cat("Mean Absolute Error:", mean_absolute_error, "\n")
## Mean Absolute Error: 1.015697
cat("Mean Squared Error:", mean_squared_error, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error: 1.594071
cat("Root Mean Squared Error:", root_mean_squared_error, "\n")
## Root Mean Squared Error: 1.262565
cat("R-Squared:", r_squared, "\n")
## R-Squared: 0.5673987
cat("Adjusted R-Squared:", adjusted_r_squared, "\n")
## Adjusted R-Squared: 0.5647545

Assumptions of linear regression

Assumption 1 : Checking Linearity

plot(model, which = 1, main = "Residuals vs. Fitted")

Inference - The red line is approximately horizontal at zero. So there exists a linear relationship between the independent variables and the dependent variable.

Assumption 2 : The mean of residuals is zero

mean(model$residuals)
## [1] 1.931897e-18

Inference : Since the mean of residuals is approximately closed to zero, this assumption holds true for this model.

Assumption 3 : Checking Multicollinearity

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
vif(model)
##          CementComponent           WaterComponent CoarseAggregateComponent 
##                 1.167425                 1.595055                 1.186289 
##   FineAggregateComponent                AgeInDays 
##                 1.550579                 1.106561

Inference - Since the vif factor is less than 4 among all the independent variables , there is no multi collinearity

Assumption 4 : Checking Normality

qqnorm(model$residuals, main = "Normality Plot of Residuals")
qqline(model$residuals, col = "red")

Inference: Since points lie exactly on the line, it is perfectly normal distribution.

Assumption 5 : Checking Homoscedasticity

plot(model, which = 3, main = "Residuals vs. Fitted (Homoscedasticity)")

Inference : As the fitted values along x increase, the residuals stay constant approximately , which represents homoscedasticity. This is more convenient as the disturbance term in Y axis is standardized.

Assumption 7: The variability in X values is positive

var(data$Strength)  
## [1] 1

Inference : The variance in the X variable above is much larger than 0. So, this assumption is satisfied.
